-- Mauritius's February Trade Gap Soars as Fuel Bill Surges
-- B y   K a m l e s h   B h u c k o r y
-- 2012-04-20T06:56:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-20/mauritius-s-february-trade-gap-soars-as-fuel-bill-surges.html
Mauritius ’s trade gap widened 44
percent in February as its fuel bill almost doubled.  The trade deficit increased to 7.56 billion rupees ($258
million) from 5.26 billion rupees a year earlier, Port Louis-
based Statistics Mauritius said in a  statement  on its website
today.  Imports increased 21 percent to 13.2 billion rupees. Fuel
purchases surged 89 percent to 4.57 billion rupees. Exports fell
by three million rupees to 5.68 billion rupees, a fifth month of
declines.  Mauritius, an Indian Ocean island nation, is a net buyer of
food and fuels. India is the only supplier as Mauritius buys all
of its fuel requirements from  Mangalore Refinery &
Petrochemicals Ltd. (MRPL) , State Trading Corp., the government’s
trading arm, said on its  website . The U.K. is the biggest buyer
of the country’s goods, purchasing 21 percent of exports in
February, followed by France at 13 percent.  The trade deficit is forecast to widen 27 percent to 92
billion rupees in 2012, Statistics Mauritius said on Feb. 28.  To contact the reporter on this story:
